---


Author Name: **Frederic Requin**
Original Redmine Message: 2030 from https://www.veripool.org



---

Hello,

this question was already asked on the forum and since I have found a solution, I would like to share it.

The solution is a variation of the Bresenham algorithm. Basically, the simulation runs with variable simulation step duration and some DPI-C calls.

Here is how the main loop looks like (with 4 generated clocks):
```
     clk0_step = (vluint64_t)0;
     clk1_step = (vluint64_t)0;
     clk2_step = (vluint64_t)0;
     clk3_step = (vluint64_t)0;
     clk0_ctr  = (vluint8_t)1;
     clk1_ctr  = (vluint8_t)1;
     clk2_ctr  = (vluint8_t)1;
     clk3_ctr  = (vluint8_t)1;

     top->STEP_TGL = (vluint8_t)0;

     // Simulation loop
     for (curr_step = (vluint64_t)0; curr_step < max_step; )
     {
         // 111 MHz clock
         if (clk0_step == curr_step)
         {
             clk0_ctr ^= 1;
             clk0_step += STEP_111M_PS;
         }
         // 133 MHz clock
         if (clk1_step == curr_step)
         {
             clk1_ctr ^= 1;
             clk1_step += STEP_133M_PS;
         }
         // 148.5 MHz clock
         if (clk2_step == curr_step)
         {
             clk2_ctr ^= 1;
             clk2_step += STEP_148M5_PS;
         }
         // 400 MHz clock
         if (clk3_step == curr_step)
         {
             clk3_ctr ^= 1;
             clk3_step += STEP_400M_PS;
         }

         // Evaluate verilated model
         top->eval ();

         #if VM_TRACE
         // Dump signals into VCD file
         if (tfp) tfp->dump(curr_step);
         #endif /* VM_TRACE */

         // Find next simulation step
         curr_step += STEP_MAX_PS;
         if (clk0_step < curr_step) curr_step = clk0_step;
         if (clk1_step < curr_step) curr_step = clk1_step;
         if (clk2_step < curr_step) curr_step = clk2_step;
         if (clk3_step < curr_step) curr_step = clk3_step;
         top->STEP_TGL ^= 1;

         if (Verilated::gotFinish()) break;
     }

```
The DPI-C functions are very simple :
```
unsigned char get_clk_111(void)
{
     return clk0_ctr;
}
unsigned char get_clk_133(void)
{
     return clk1_ctr;
}
unsigned char get_clk_148_5(void)
{
     return clk2_ctr;
}
unsigned char get_clk_400(void)
{
     return clk3_ctr;
}

```
STEP_TGL is an "irregular" clock that toggles each time a clock event occurs on one of the 4 clocks.

The verilog code that generates the clocks is :
```
     import "DPI-C" function bit get_clk_111();
     import "DPI-C" function bit get_clk_133();
     import "DPI-C" function bit get_clk_148_5();
     import "DPI-C" function bit get_clk_400();

     initial begin
         clk_111   = 1'b0;
         clk_133   = 1'b0;
         clk_148_5 = 1'b0;
         clk_400   = 1'b0;
     end

     always@(posedge tb_top.STEP_TGL) begin : TOGGLE_RISE
         clk_111   = get_clk_111();
         clk_133   = get_clk_133();
         clk_148_5 = get_clk_148_5();
         clk_400   = get_clk_400();
     end

     always@(negedge tb_top.STEP_TGL) begin : TOGGLE_FALL
         clk_111   = get_clk_111();
         clk_133   = get_clk_133();
         clk_148_5 = get_clk_148_5();
         clk_400   = get_clk_400();
     end

```
I have attached a complete verilator example.

This opens up the possibility of simulating PLLs, delays, etc...

Maybe a special API can be added to pre-compute the clocks stimulis ?

